Even if their criticism is only said of their work (I did not fare so well there), it still preys on common cognitive distortions and? Honestly? Not a single piece of crit these types offer is a better teacher than experience or someone more convinced of how wonderful you are.

it's my biggest regret in my artistic life that I kept such highly critical people so closely for what a lot of peers describe as their most unrestrained periods. I don't have any record of the stories I wanted to tell bc this sort of company can really freeze your hand!

with the webcomics talk going on rn, let me just say: avoid keeping the company of other storytellers with open, vocal impossible standards for themselves or "not good enough" attitudes. it's like lice and can really gum up your creative freedom and the point of this medium!

Idk. My heart hurts a lot, seeing and experiencing this sort of hatred and rejection from within queer community, but I know things feel and go a little better on all accts when a young person can come to me with a good-faith question abt queerness and we can talk it out.

This way of thinking of queerness is that of wanting some sort of club with passwords and people you can not let in, rather than a community garden that's run by collective xp. And I think inviting young people into the garden starts with cultivating an irresistibly kind one.

and doing what little I can to make spaces where I'm the adult one where you can safely not know something...where there's positive reinforcement and human connection that doesn't have the sort of neatly summarized organization young minds and the culture at large wants.

It looks like teaching queer history through art and having class be more about empathetic critical thinking ("here is the historical context that informs this piece of queer art; now, imagine you're the artist/subject and tell me your thinking here") than drawing, sometimes,

Truthfully I only know how to approach such a HUGE cultural/technological bundle of stuff with a small-scale palliative approach...(trying to) put out art that can't work without nuance, doing my best to be the adult that enables them to fear having the wrong answers less...

I've been thinking about LRT and honestly my biggest takeaway is that this is consequence of growing up in a culture where bite-sized viral content is  an overwhelming source of positive reinforcement and peer-to-peer connection, discouraging necessary messy real-life XP (thread)

it's been rough recently being able to make and regard my work as worthwhile...but however i feel, i don't think anyone could call my work careless or empty, and that counts for something!

i think art is, as the powerpoint slides back at the top say, most effective backed by a lot of brainpower...this is also the sort of thinking i put into things like character design and composition, and I think part of my unique stamp as an artist

i'm not even getting into the the process of the actual printing or ink drawing....but you can see how much thought my approach to illustration takes! i am and will always be many thoughts, head full, and you can't take that away from my art practice lmao

either way, you can see why i decided on having the images superimposed on top of each other for the final product! i originally planned on risograph, but man...i love to screenprint, and the allure of blacklight was very alluring indeed lol https://t.co/B4ISUfBilL

oh! and i just remembered -- removing "as above, so below" entirely since it depends on the idea of heaven and hell...since baphy was designed based on christian dogma, i thought that the goal of "recentering" the point of view called for removing it entirely

the way i answered the question was to look to other points of view and representations of the different 'pieces' of baphomet and associated imagery. a long-eared goat, a moon in place of 🔥, a lotus as a representation of seed (vs something phallic), a softer, fatter body, etc. https://t.co/WHtj9M44Mw

that then turned into breaking down the actual imagery of Baphomet and questioning what each piece both represents and implies, then asking the question "how would I change it from the propaganda the image is founded in? how do i make this traditionally warm & welcoming?"

so i started this knowing only that I wanted to work with the /image/ of Baphomet, and that I'd take the concept further based off of what information i could find and riff off of...here's what I ended up with after a couple days of just plain ole research and ideation! https://t.co/pc6nv6H2gG

that can be acted upon with just talking on social media -- at worst this turns into the witch-hunts and bullying stemming from good intentions (i.e. the pr*ship/ant*ship nonsense). & I'm not even getting into how privilege, esp white privilege, interacts with all this...

The truth is that we can't give "proper" witnessing and justice to every stranger on the internet, and meaningful prevention of harm is often v specific to each community and person and etc. But at this point in time, we think of all three as one blob of feelings & actions

It's frustrating because on one hand, there are callouts out on SNS that are urgent and necessary to keep someone safe and prevent further harm, messiness of the situation be damned...but I feel many more create more harm  bc of this relationship sns creates b/t capital & healing

(those three things have to be separate for greatest efficacy, because they serve different people. "Witnessing" serves the victim (singular), "justice" serves all victims, "prevention" serves people, at large. )

But bc this occurs in a public way, because the numbers are linked to publicity, the actions of "seeking witnesses to my pain" and "seeking action to prevent further harm" AND "seeking justice" become a big soup, rather than three distinct goals and actions...

I think a crucial part of healing from trauma, esp one caused by an abuser, is being witnessed in your pain, but I think SNS has really skewed our perception of what "witnessing" means-- we've attached a numerical capital to it where we don't feel witnessed without number go up

this isn't brought on by any one thing in particular, moreso just stewing with thoughts for a while, but I feel like so much of "callout culture" is much more a form of trauma dumping than it is seeking protection, prevention, or justice? And this is inextricable from sns (con't)

Dunno. I just need to chew this fat, and I hope you'll chew it with me in examining how you're actually gonna do stuff to stopaapihate and so on.

I suppose this also goes into the way wokeness on the 2021 internet is a brand more than it is any real amount of action. About doing things correctly so you get praise and can win conflict, rather than act from critical thinking and deep empathy.

And I don't want to keep solidifying my presence as just That Asian Person I Can Leech Woke Words And Labor From. I'm also Margaret, this weird artist that likes to screenprint and draw pretty knights and a million other things.

I've felt obligated for weeks to like......say things. Make my presence and stance known, but at the same time, I feel like that's obvious if you know a thing about the person I am. My work, the way I exist, the way I speak and care and love, that all speaks for itself.
It's a big tangled knot. I see more and more how convenience and positive feedback is the only currency most people want to barter in when it comes to doing antiracist work.

Pretty much the only work (teaching or art-wise) I'm approached for is that of AAPI empowerment. And that's to be expected, with how I built myself, but I do feel more and more that I exist to others as a tool of my race, and not an artist whose body of work they respect.

Taking time to untangle the racist dynamics of my own (mixed white & asian) family. Embedding antiracist norms and dialogue in my work as an educator -- arming every student I get with the critical thinking skills to notice, deconstruct, and reconstruct racist norms.

I look back on a flood of work I was making about asian identity, food, and community-building and I feel both tired and like I was impossibly naive. Right now I feel like the most meaningful antiracist work I've done is in the little actions.

I have witnessed lots of other BIPOC express similar sentiments. Antiracist work is engaged with on an urgent and performative basis. It is rarely attended to in the smaller cracks that enable the dam of overt violence news bothers to cover to break.

One thing I feel like we keep dealing with is that antiracist action comes and goes in trends. The urgency spikes with the visibility of hate. The antiracist action of the bulk of people -- non-asian /and/ AAPI -- will occur only in that timeframe.

I corner /everything/ I do in deliberately antiracist action. My small interactions, how I use my body, how I use what platforms I have, how visibly I exist as Asian, how visibly I exist as mixed-race, and how every action of mine as a professional affects how things go.
A few years ago I had a boundless amount of energy to give to AAPI initiative, community, and service, and I really felt fine with it being a dominating part of my career. Now I'm not so sure.

Not to get like, super real on main after being disappeared for a while, but I dunno. I've obviously been thinking a lot about my role in preventing and ending xenophobia against AAPI folks. Thinking a lot about the nature of performative disclosure. (thread)

here are some reasons why you might prefer thick lines: 
- more drastic changes in line weight  
- more room to use the texture of your tool 
- punchy, bold look
- prevents you from getting lost in the sauce of overdetailing 
- you just enjoy yourself more using them

....but none of these things are skills that are *exclusive* to working with thin lines. i suspect refining these skills is why some folks felt like using thin lines made them better artists, not any actual "thin lines > thick lines" truth or whatever

imho, here are things using thin lines can help *teach* you: 
- being decisive with where you actually put your lines 
- forcing you to not fudge drawing things you find difficult 
- using composition and posing to show where you want the viewer to focus 
- and plenty more!

thin lines can make your art seem more precise, maybe more clean, and they also create room for more detail, but none of those things necessarily make you a better or more skillful illustrator. i really hate the idea that the more detail you can cram in, the better your work is

the other day i saw a rando advise to "draw with thinner lines" as a fast way to improve your art and: no! hard disagree. there are some useful things you can learn by using thin lines, but this isn't the first time i've seen someone equate "thin lines = more skill" (thread)

- no doomsaying or doomscrolling.
- if you are approaching a despair event horizon, it is OK to do nice things for yourself so you can find the guts to keep fighting. 
- there are too many good and vulnerable people who are more important than declaring anything a lost cause.

- do not participate in bad faith arguments, whether in refuting or starting them. 
- disengage with social media, or at least opt to mute, block, or unfollow before you spend hours that could be spent on direct action on an argument on the internet that will serve very few ppl.

- decide on a concrete amount of time every day, week, etc. to dedicate to Doing the Right Thing that doesn't involve self-reflection, pontificating, or being on social media. mutual aid, direct action, organizing, demonstrating, pressuring electeds, etc.

- do not engage in anything that will make you unproductively angry.

no education reform will stick without wringing every cent out of the wealthy and defunding the police and having that money go into funding schools. think about what would happen if we had the public budget to have all teachers be paid on tax dollars & be tuition-free for all.

which is really all in service to say: no school should need HR. no school should have a board of anything that isn't made up of its own current staff. teaching positions shouldn't be filled based on benefitting the school (prestige, research initiatives, etc.) over the students.

don't mistake this for an argument against having an institution of education in the first place. it's just education that actually serves all people effectively can't exist within capitalistic practice and they very much do rn, in culture and in practice.

while we're mid-pandemic and still remote learning, there is literally no higher education price that is worth your dollars right now. half the learning that goes on in college is from getting to safely exploring a mini-community where you can fuck up w/o dire consequence.

i attended both academic & art school for college: the whole institution of education was built on fuckshit foundations that need to be completely redone. having a good higher education xp is more or less a game of luck & privilege, as it is with many things.

I work a weird-ass niche but I hope this helped someone out. And if anyone else has comparable work and rates, please lmk!

I have seen an overall decrease in pay due to COVID and shifting to digital learning. This is largely because my direct contact with students has decreased drastically (1-2/day vs 6-8) and my clients have less budget to work with.

Festival activity development (2+ days' worth of content): negotiate only, since I tailor it heavily to the client's needs and ability. If I'm required to be present, I don't accept less than ($25 x predicted # of hrs worked + $150 + cost of materials).
I also do zine workshops for $0, usually in exchange for other goods (i.e. a discounted show table) or if I (and only I) deem it appropriate.

Single-day zine workshops (typically ~4-6 hrs): $150-300. Fees go up as predicted attendance increases. I supply initial materials, clients supplement with what they have available. I also supply access to my zine library as part of the fee.

Printed educational materials (500+ copies of 6-10 pp limited-color fully illustrated zines + activity development + adapting clients' ideas + 2-3 stages of revisions) - ~$1k, but I also foot all printing costs and any extra labor fees (flatters, consultants, etc.).

FWIW: I don't think there's a hashtag, but as a freelance art educator: 

Std hourly teaching rate: $25/hr 
Summer camps: $860/wk for ~7hr day, fully responsible for 18-20 minors + full curriculum development. I don't provide supplies.

RT @XpertDemon: These past few weeks have been so heavy, sending what light I can. Thought it would be useful to reshare this syllabus “Bla…

But we can't rely on an inherently racist institution (for now, I hope) to do all that work for us. You've got to do this with whatever family or friends' kids or friends of your kids you can. Awkwardness and ruffled feathers be absolutely damned.

Something I believe in very fiercely is that the sticking power of revolution also depends on those of us who transform and communicate information professionally. And it's up to us nonblack adults to give kiddos the care and patience required to unlearn antiblackness asap.

I don't know if your interactions will go as smoothly as that, but whew. I teach a lot of really brilliant kids who're already very, very inundated by the racist culture around 'em. If they're young enough to do racist things, they're young enough to unlearn them.

The kiddo in question accepted that and clearly considered it. In my experience, young folks are really receptive to transforming their thinking like that, as long as you phrase it right and don't make them feel bad for it! 

The conversation continued and life went on.

So, what came out of my mouth was: 

"Hold on just a moment. All that means is that the police think he committed the crime. That doesn't mean he's good or bad or that he even did it. I don't think the police know any better than you or I who's a bad or good person."
(You might've heard of "Freddish" -- the steps of translation Mr. Rogers took to communicate an important concept to his very young demographic. Similar idea, but aged up.) https://t.co/V0zwkMWFjx

Instead, take a couple steps and moments to restructure the thought. Use language that 
1) dissents the problematic ideal 
2) doesn't place blame on the young person 
3) actively shows the young person they have agency
4) assumes they're just as smart as you (just have less xp)

This isn't the kid's fault, of course, but that really didn't stop a gut reaction I had of wanting to cut in with a "we don't say that" in a stern tone, but that fundamentally doesn't teach that kid ANYTHING except what words to not use around me and me specifically.

This sort of thinking starts super early, this was a pretty young kiddo. Pro-police culture and this kind of moral absolutisim is embedded into EVERYTHING. How we code jobs, play games, and especially media where policing is equated to the lawfulness that solves chaos.

A couple years ago, I overhear some of the kiddos I'm in charge of having a conversation. I don't know the full context but I did hear one of them say, "well, I know he's a bad person, because the police arrested him."
(disclaimer: I'm not The Authority on all things educatey and teachery and child psychologey, I just have some XP I hope can help you do good in your small interactions with young folks.)

I want to encourage other nonblack adults who have contact with nonblack young people to be constantly thinking about their interactions as a means of inspiring restorative justice and correcting pro-police ideals. Here's an anecdote of what I mean.

this isn't a free pass to go to la-la land and skip out on direct action, it's more like "you need to feed, clean, and care for yourself if you're going to have the brain and endurance to do anything worth a damn."

treating things that keep your head above water as stuff you have to with-hold just for the sake of it doesn't work. at worst, it's performative, and at best, it teaches your brain to mistake guilt and deprivation with productivity. i've learned from experience it's doesn't work.

hey fellow nonblack folks: don't confuse "don't look away/be present and active" for "i must say something" & also don't confuse "don't tag out just bc you're uncomfortable" with "i will uselessly self-flagellate instead of basic care necessary to act meaningfully"

@annabelledroid YEAH THIS LMAO
i really just went on a big bundle of Thinking A Lot Very Publicly right there, but hey! i love seeing other people chew over their ideas like this, and maybe it'll be some food for thought for you!

that's not to say that reflecting the oppressive, dystopic shit we suffer isn't important or valuable, it's just I think we also have to offer work that gives us the guts to take direct action and be kinder by ways of hope and the assurance we do deserve good futures!

we all need a certain amount of play in our lives and i dislike the idea that one genre is so precious that it's exempt from that? and i like even more that contemporary anticapitalistic genres (i.e. cottagecore, solarpunk) envision life that succeeds past the dystopia

I don't think there's a problem if someone wants to play with the neon lights and sweet robot shit and doesn't wanna also comment on the very big and exhausting subject of how to destroy capitalism. (there's def ways it can be done irresponsibly, but that's a different convo!)

i'm admittedly not at all invested in the uh, upcoming big cyberpunk game coming out, and spend a lot of my time as an art teacher teaching my students to not feel shame in their tastes and decisions, but like....I also don't see a problem if someone just likes the aesthetics!
and I get a lot of joy and learn SO SO MUCH when I see other creators do the same!! (cough cough go listen to @Friends_Table 's counter/WEIGHT )

it's like, I doubt I could bridge my narrative voice to the tension, dissection of technology, and anticapitalism i associate w/cyberpunk unless I used my personal connections, esp in how I'm combining my love of silly mecha anime w/processing postcolonial realities.

but the aesthetics and color palette I choose reflect the tropical and distinctly not-urbanized...it's built on vague memories I have of Thailand as a kid and a trip to São Tomé where I was wrestling with a lot of complicated feelings.

https://t.co/RTxtu385QU

like, for me personally? I think I'm wrestling most with cyberpunky vibes when I work with my mecha story Vulture Song (& its offshoots I'm still building) bc a lot of anticapitalism to me is abt understanding and reappropriating a postcolonial world and its violent tech?

i'd like it much more if we appropriately assigned more value to cool, progressive people who've committed the labor to making their stories progressive, rather than trusting more in a pre-set foundation of aesthetics and ideas that will inevitably have blind spots

bc like...1) word meanings change, and that's ok 2) I'm all right with no genre being inherently tied to progressive thought, bc very few genres are inherently progressive. it's the people and thinkers and makers behind each individual story and how they transform those tools.

ngl, even if it's not true to everything in the genre, so much of my early xp's with cyberpunk & its aesthetics were couched in orientalism? and I'm sort of fine that "cyberpunk" as a term has become more representative of an aesthetic or atmosphere

i think....the anticorporate, anticapitalist flavors of cyberpunk have transformed to be much more idiosyncratic genres and takes, bc we all have a different xp's w/ all the ways capitalism drives society to ruin and how we'd like to seize power and fuck it all up (a thread)

I think this is also a credit to AO3'S literal structure and being inherently not about generating capital. It's a small vision of what creating feels like outside of capitalism, and I think it can be a vital breath for a lot of us still struggling to find any kind of success.

It's refreshing to create unattached to capital and success. It's helped me panic less about the state of my career and if I just suck, actually, and just make small stories and feel happy they can entertain or make people feel/think a little better.

just posting a story that didn't take 10000 stages of drawing, drafting, and several months/years, not having to worry abt self promo, and getting very kind and positive feedback and some concrete numbers that help me feel like I'm not dumping labor into a void? V helpful.

But don't forget about keeping in touch with what you want for yourself! Like I said earlier, there's no surviving crises without hope. So work your butt off to think about what you, just you, REALLY want, even if it's just a good booty call or a kickass dinner.

6) I know it's really, really hard in times like these, but think towards the future and what you want out of it. (What you deserve!) Think both big and small: as small as "I want to go get ice cream with friends" or as big as "I'LL DESTROY CAPITALISM WITH MY OWN TWO HANDS"

You might not be able to escape these thing being dumped on you, which sucks. But I promise you'll feel like you're drowning a little less if you know it's inappropriate in the first place. You're just one person, after all.

- being the sole point of contact for a person 
- being a 'villain' 
- taking the burden of someone else's pain
- weathering screaming/yelling 

Some of these, like helping someone shoulder pain, is a two-way street that's OK *ONLY* if you enthusiastically agree to doing it.

5) Remember that these are not appropriate things to be laid on you:

- solving another adult's emotional problems 
- solving the entire world's problems 
- being a 'rescuer'   
- taking the blame for things you didn't do 
- predicting how your actions will define someone's mood

I don't care what the people around you or your brainworms are telling you -- you DO deserve to feel nice and enjoy life!!! There's no solving or surviving crises without hope, and there's no hope without some joy in your life!!! You don't have to be productive to earn fun!!!

4) Stay engaged with pleasure and fun!!! And I mean ACTIVE pleasure, not just rote numbing kinds of things. Take time regularly to do stuff that makes your heart soar!! Listen to music? watch anime? dance? fantasize wildly about becoming a JoJo with a ripped bod and stand? do it!

If you express them and are met with resistance, don't give into revising them or buckling under the pressure. If you aren't put into physical harm's way for it, don't ever compromise them. If you make it clear they're immutable, people tend to follow.

3) Decide on new boundaries, or decide on them in the first place. These might look like: 
- "If you insult me, then I won't engage." 
- "I won't interrupt my work for you. Ask me again only when I tell you I'm available."
- "After 8PM, you can't ask me for things."

Often these bouts are brought on by the toxic person managing their stress, anxiety, and pain poorly, and they put it through the lens of self-importance or incorrect blame. That's not on you to fix. Do what you can to tune out and leave and let that air escape that balloon.

2) Use detachment strategies. If someone's railing on you and you feel tempted to boil over and retaliate or completely shrink back and take it? Resist both those instincts. If you can physically leave the room, do it. Don't continue the conversation.

It's like. I feel like a lot of this grief is easier to deal with when we restructure it so it's less about you shouldering the weight of 943094309403 peoples' 4842732830290302 mistakes over 3920392320 years and more about effective and caring action you can do on the regular.

Small changes are still changes. Good is always worth doing, because there's no magical power that will sweep the world and fix everything, and every positive change that makes even one person's life a little bit better is infinitely valuable.

But to that end, it's valuable to commit yourself to being as many drops in as many buckets for progressive thinking and radical initiatives, and it's just as valuable to think of those drops you contribute as important and encouraging others to do the same.

Paraphrased, it was about how no one singular thing is ever truly a catalyst for change -- it's built on tons of things all stacking on top of one another, and it's rare you'll be that exact drop in the bucket that makes everything spill over.

I get super stressed about this when I teach kiddos subjects that combine sustainability and art, but a quote from one of the Wertheim sisters (I'm sorry I don't remember which one!!! >_< ) from their hyperbolic coral reef project really helped re-orient my thinking--

The other part of that is valuing every small action you take. Not in an 'I can be lazy about my activism' kind of way, but like, 'every small decision I make has meaning and is a drop in the bucket for change.'

I got distant nieces and nephews that might live to see it become uninhabitable because of climate change. It made it easier to get out of 'I'm sad there's no snow and I feel too small to do anything about it' and into 'I want to help their future be good.'

I was feeling stressed and sad about the seasons (particularly winter) but felt way more able to think my way out of quagmire-y grief into more of a call to action grief when I thought about relatives in Bangkok.
and really, truly the most effective way I've found to cope is re-orienting the narrative to "well, what can I do to help other people who are feeling the same way or are in a more dire situation?"

You deserve to make the work any version of you would want, whether the kid you, the current you, the future you, or any of the above.

Using skills outside of sheer artmaking isn’t cheating. It doesn’t prove your art is somehow inherently worse if you need to combine your practice with other skills, like teaching, organizing, or entertaining, to find a sustainable practice.

Making self-published work that isn’t 100% completely you serving your own bullshit is a great way to get hired for work you don’t want to do, build a dissatisfying practice, and burn out quickly and what will feel like futilely.
